It is defined as the difference between the most recently reported trailing 12-month operating cash flow per share and that of 4 quarters ago for a stock divided by its trading price.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month operating cash flow per share for a stock divided by its trading price.
It is defined as the difference between the the trailing 12-month operating cash flow per share and that of 12-quarters ago for a stock divided by its trading price.
It is defined as the difference between the the trailing 12-month cash flow per share and that of 12-quarter ago comparable trailing 12-month cash flow for a stock divided by its trading price.
It is defined as the sum of trailing 12-month growth flow value per share for a stock divided by its trading price. Growth flow is the sum of Research & Development expenses and reported net income.
It is defined as a company's next 4-quarter mean earnings estimate multiplied by the mean long-term growth rate forecast, scaled by its trading price.
It is defined as the beta coefficient to Change in Industrial Production, which is estimated by a 60 month multiple regression of returns on several macroeconomic factors.
It is defined as the most recent trailing 12-month operating and nonoperating income per share before provisions for income taxes and minority interest for a stock delfated by its  the trading price.
It is defined as the beta coefficient to Change in Credit Risk Premium, which is estimated by a 60 month multiple regression of returns on several macroeconomic factors.
It is defined as the time weighted Sales per share for FY1 and FY2 divided by its price
It is defined as the FY1 estimate of  Sales value per share divided by its trading price
It is defined as the most recently reported trailing 12-month sales per share for a stock deflated by its trading price.
It is defined as the difference between the most recently reported trailing 12-month earnings per share and that of 4 quarters ago for a stock deflated by its trading price.
It is defined as the difference between realized profitability and expected one which is calculated from a regression model.

It is defined as the most recent book value of net assets per share (NAV) by the closing price. NAV is calculated in general form by taking the total assets of a company and subtracting the value of the company's intangible assets (goodwill, patents,etc.) minus current and long-term liabilities.
It evaluates stocks based on their historical 12-month market (S&P 500) adjusted excess return (the Y intercept from an OLS regression equation) using a proprietary rational decay function.
It is defined as the 6-month average of the monthly change in the average analyst recommendation.

It is defined as the difference between current accounts receivable and the expected level of accounts receivable (multiplying the prior year's closing account balance by the growth in sales in the trailing 12-months) scaled by the total assets.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month earnings per share before extra items less the trailing 12-month dividends per share by ex-date divided by the average book equity per share in the same period.
It is defined as a stock's current book-to-market ratio (BP) minus the average of  the BPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the BPs over the same period.

It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month cash flow-to-price ratio (CFP) minus the average of  the CFPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the CFPs over the same period.

It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month EBITDA per share-to-price ratio (EBITDAP) minus the average of the EBITDAPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the EBITDAPs over the same period.

It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month earnings per share before extra items-to-price ratio (EP) minus the average of  the EPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the EPs over the same period.

It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month free cash flow-to-price ratio (FCFP) minus the average of  the FCFPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the FCFPs over the same period.

It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month operating cash flow-to-price ratio (OCFP) minus the average of  the OCFPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the OCFPs over the same period.
It is defined as a stock's current trailing 12-month sales-to-price ratio (SP) minus the average of  the SPs in the last 60-month scaled by the standard deviation of the SPs over the same period.
It is defined as a stock's 12-month relative price-strength (PS) minus the PSs of all stocks in the same industry deflated by the standard deviation of these PSs.
It is defined as the standard error of the slope of the least squares regression line for a stock's last 60-month monthly returns against the S&P 500 Index returns.

It is defined as the change in a stock's current analysts mean earnings estimate for fiscal year 1 less that of three months ago, scaled by the standard deviation of analyst forecasts as of three months ago.

It is defined as the change in a stock's current analysts mean earnings estimate for fiscal year 2 less that of three months ago, scaled by the standard deviation of analyst forecasts as of three months ago.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month total sales divided by the number of employees at the end of the last reported fiscal year.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month income before extra items divided by the average of common equity in the same period.

It is defined as the trailing 12-month net income and interest expenses divided by the average reported invested capital, which equals the sum of common equity,long-term debt,minority interest and preferred stock.
It is defined as the latest reported quarterly operating income divided by 12-Month lagged total assets.
It is defined as the interquartile range of stock's daily total return over the trailing one month.

It is defined as the absolute value of the difference between the yearly percent change in trailing 12-month sales per share and the yearly  percent change in trailing 12-month diluted earnings per share before extraordinary items.
It is defined as the difference between the trailing 12-month sales (SALE) and the SALE 20 quarters ago and then deflated by the average of the SALEs in the prior 20 quarters.
It is defined as the difference between the yearly change in most recent reported quarterly sales and the yearly change in the quarterly gross profit margin.
It is defined as the difference between the yearly percent change in trailing 12-month sales and the yearly percent change in accounts receivable.
It is defined as the beta coefficient to Change in Housing Starts, which is estimated by a 60 month multiple regression of returns on several macroeconomic factors.
It is defined as the standard deviation of a stock's monthly returns in the prior 60 months.
It is defined as the skewness of the distribution of a stock's daily excess (compared to the S&P 500 index) price returns in last 90 days. Skewness = 3*(Mean-Median])/Standard Deviation.
It is defined as the skewness (measure of lack of symmetry) of the distribution of a stock's daily price returns in last 90 days. Skewness = 3*(Mean-Median])/Standard Deviation.
It is defined as the slope coefficient between monthly dates and the corresponding trailing 12-month earnings per share before extra items in the prior 20 quarters
It is defined as the 4-week lagged slope coefficient of the least squares regression line of the last 52-week weekly stock's closing price against the corresponding weekly dates.
It is defined as the 4-week lagged slope coefficient of the least squares regression line of the last 66-week weekly stock's closing price against the corresponding weekly dates.
It is defined as the standard deviation of analyst earnings estimates for fiscal year 1 divided by the mean consensus forecast.
It is defined as the standard deviation of analyst earnings estimates for fiscal year 2 divided by the mean consensus forecast.

It is defined as the absolute value of the difference between the yearly percent change in trailing 12-month operating cash flow per share and the yearly percent change in trailing 12-month diluted EPS before extraordinary items.
It is defined as the the trailing 12-month earnings per share before extra items (EPS) minus 4 quarter ago EPS deflated by the average total assets per share.
It is defined as the consensus recommendation for a company.
It is defined as the difference between the actual earnings per share and consensus forecasts prior to the announcement date, scaled by price at the end of the quarter.

It is the maximum growth rate a firm can sustain without having to increase financial leverage. It is defined as: ROE x (1 - dividend-payout ratio), where ROE is the trailing 12-month return on book equity.
It is defined as the market value of equity (E) plus debt (D) divided by assets (A), or (E + D)/A. D is measured using book values.
It equals (Cash Flow from Operations + Interest Paid + Tax Paid)/ (Interest + Principal Paid).
It is defined as the percent change in a company's trailing 12-month total sales (TOTSALE) as compared to the TOTSALE one year ago.

It is defined as: (CORREL*(260-2)^.5)/(1-CORREL^2)^.5.  CORREL is the correlation coefficient between the natural logarithm of stock daily closing price and the corresponding daily dates in last 260 days.
It is defined as the difference between the trailing 12-month net income and the trailing 12-month operating cash flow scaled by the beginning total assets.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month capital expenditures per share for a stock divided by its trading price.

It is defined as the trailing 12 month operating income (before depreciation and amortization) divided by enterprise value (EV).  EV = Equity Market Value + Long-term Debt + Short-term Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash.

It is defined as the trailing 12-month sales for a stock divided by the most recent enterprise value (EV). EV = Equity Market Value + Long-term Debt + Short-term Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash& Cash Equivalents.
It is defined as the time weighted EBITDA/Enterprise Value for FY1 and FY2.
It is defined as the 6-month average of the time weighted sum of the FY1 and FY2 earnings estimate revisions.
It is defined as the 6-month average of the time weighted sum of the FY1 and FY2 earnings estimate revisions adjusted by the standard deviations of earnings estimates.

It is defined as the variance of a stock's monthly residual return in last 24-month. The monthly residual return equals the stock's monthly return minus the product of the multiplication of a stock's proprietary 60-month Beta by the S&P 500 index monthly return.

It is defined as the trailing 12-month free cash flow (FCF) for a stock scaled by its enterprise value (EV).  EV = Equity Market Value + Long-term Debt + Short-term Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash.
It is defined as the trailing 12-month operating cash flow per share for a stock divided by its per share Enterprise Value.
It is defined as the consensus forward 12-month earnings per share forecast divided by the sum of market value of common equity per share and book value of long-term debt per share.
It equals to a stock's most recent daily trading volume divided by the average daily trading volume in previous 50 trading days.
It is defined as the most recently reported quarterly operating income before depreciation divided by the quarterly long-term debt interest expenses.
It is defined as the 6 month moving average of average monthly turnover ratio, which equals the number of shares traded each day deflated by the total number of shares outstanding.
It is defined as the monthly total trading volume divided by the most recently reported total outstanding shares.
It is defined as the moving average of a stock's prices in last 30 weeks divided by the moving average of its prices in last 75 weeks.
It is defined as a stock's most recent weekly closing price divided by its weekly closing price 26 weeks ago.
It is defined as a stock's price change from week t-43 to week t-4.
It is defined as the beta coefficient to Change in Market Volatility, which is estimated by a 60 month multiple regression of returns on several macroeconomic factors.
It is defined as the conditional square of the correlation between monthly dates and the corresponding trailing 12-month earnings per share before extra items in the prior 20 quarters.
It is defined as the standard deviation of the last 20-Month trailing 12-month earnings per share (EPS) divided by the mean of these EPSs
It is defined as the average of three normalized earnings calculated by ROE, NPM and EPS FY2, scaled by price.
It is defined as the beta coefficient to Change in Slope of Term Structure, which is estimated by a 60 month multiple regression of returns on several macroeconomic factors.

It is defined as the trailing 12-month income before extra items less the trailing 12-month operating cash flow, then scaled by the average total assets, then minus the scaled difference for the same quarter one year ago.
It is defined as the difference between the most recent reported quarterly total liabilities as a percentage of the reported total assets and the percentage for the same quarter one year ago.

It is defined as the most recent quarterly reported gross profit margin minus the margin for the same quarter one year ago. Gross profit margin equals the difference between sales and cost of goods sold then scaled by the sales.
It is defined as the most recent trailing 12-month income before extra items as a percentage of total assets minus the percentage for the same quarter one year ago.
It is defined as the yearly arithmetic change in the ratio of trailing-twelve-month earnings before extraordinary items (Quarterly data) divided by current total book equity.
It is defined as the yearly percentage change in the ratio of the TTM earnings before extraordinary items (Quarterly data) divided by current total book equity.
